000130_​generated_data
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_generated_data" obligation="normative">
<title>Generated data</title>
<p id="_90ff58c2-7a92-2a2b-6a85-763a304eeaf5">Consumers may need data in its unmodified format and as a derived product e.g. ortho-rectified image. Both can be utilized for a variety of spatiotemporal analyses.</p>

<p id="_287393c1-f92a-1197-fd62-a32c18ab4b1d">Examples of a WAMI image size are 60, 96, 144, 150, 1100, 1600, 1800, or 2200 megapixels or more. The pixels may be 8-bit or 16-bit, may contain color, black and white, VNIR, MWIR or other EM-frequency ranges. An example WAMI image may contain 60 MB to 12 GB or more of uncompressed data. At 1600 megapixels or 1.6 gigapixels per frame, one WAMI image would be 772 times larger than full HD.</p>
2



000171_web_​services
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_web_services" obligation="normative">
<title>Web services</title>
<p id="_3bf1d5de-35bf-decc-0658-992691bc819b">To retrieve data in forms stated above, a consumer needs global access to WAMI data. This is a problem of communication, performance and scale. If we break the general problem of WAMI data dissemination down into smaller problems, each standing by itself, we can address them separately and simply. This approach produces functional, modular, small, and independent solutions.</p>

<p id="_764012c8-ecce-7225-2b98-291754c4820c">Data is remote, often times in limited compute environments. It is hard for a client to be next to the data. This solution should make it so that it is not necessary for a data consumer to be next to the data. Therefore, each independent solution is a web service, implementing a well-designed grammar meant for today’s defense networks and the Internet. WAMI web services define the grammar. The format is controlled by various format standardization bodies. Customers dictate which format is required by them. Service implementations cater to customer needs.</p>
2

Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_wami_web_services" obligation="normative">
<title>WAMI web services</title>
<p id="_c188d1e5-b716-de0e-9d2b-98fb70b704db">This section answers the question of “What types of web services should serve WAMI data?” To identify these services, the first step is to set ground rules to maintain design focus.</p>

<ol id="_96521a12-c293-3716-81ab-a8a9887832ec" type="arabic"> <li> <p id="_08021e71-130b-264a-db1b-abce2390cc0f">AWAMI service should perform no more than one task and do it well.</p>

000339_virtual_​file_​system
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_virtual_file_system" obligation="normative">
<title>Virtual File System</title>
<p id="_13d6096e-ee4b-e221-ec16-dd4c4c009fa3">While SOA caters to today’s internet model, file access is still common. Tools require image and video files, and XML. Vendors may not have time to implement HTTP services. They may have to support legacy client tools that are many years old, and have been adapted to suite immediate WAMI needs. If a file-based WAMI service was available, it could assist in a phased migration to web services.</p>

<clause id="_avoid_vendor_lockdown" obligation="normative">
2

000391_restful_​http
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_restful_http" obligation="normative">
<title>RESTful HTTP</title>
<p id="_582c5ffa-71c5-da5e-30ce-309eac3db6fd">The term RESTful HTTP is used to represent a stateless HTTP request/response model, a client and server processing one independent HTTP request at a time. WAMI services use a RESTful architecture.</p>

000428_time
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_time" obligation="normative">
<title>Time</title>
<p id="_65cce657-3d1b-1436-0dba-6e02c937971f">Time value or range is set by the TIME parameter as absolute frame numbers or as ISO time. Frame based access is efficient, TIME based access is flexible. Both forms of time are explicit and do not leave room for ambiguity. The tables below have been captured from the original document to summarize the syntax. A client can ask for image data or metadata:</p>

<ol id="_a04f1ad2-04d2-d34e-2730-5c0ed3e020af" type="arabic"> <li> <p id="_3000f59e-a32a-682a-d02d-bc2725e17513">At a single instant in time</p>

000609_image_​service
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_image_service" obligation="normative">
<title>Image Service</title>
<p id="_c5e88095-9eef-4eb3-dc24-5a610f8e0032">As an image and metadata flipbook service, the Image Service or IS delivers a view into WAMI collections. It delivers derived content as maps and metadata from the original camera-space data or from data that is already available in a derived content space. See examples in <xref target="annex-examples"/>.</p>

000650_video_​service

<clause id="_video_service" obligation="normative">
<title>Video Service</title>
<p id="_03b117f9-a769-338c-b1dd-9a598626724e">The Video Service is notionally identical to the IS. Instead of a flipbook of images, it delivers a video clip of those images. If the content format supports the addition of metadata, it is included. See <xref target="annex-subsec-vs"/> in <xref target="annex-examples"/>.</p>
